Increased carbon dioxide decreases haemoglobin-oxygen affinity","Increased carbon dioxide increases haemoglobin-oxygen affinity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EBohr effect describes how increased carbon dioxide decreases haemoglobin\u0027s affinity for oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E. This physiological mechanism facilitates oxygen unloading in metabolically active tissues where carbon dioxide levels are high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemperature changes affect oxygen binding\u003C/strong\u003E - While temperature does influence oxygen binding to haemoglobin, this describes a separate physiological mechanism from the Bohr effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased carbon dioxide increases haemoglobin-oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E - Although this relationship is true, it represents the reverse scenario and is not the primary definition of the Bohr effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen levels affect carbon dioxide transport\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the Haldane effect, which is a distinct physiological process from the Bohr effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased carbon dioxide increases haemoglobin-oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as it states the opposite relationship to the Bohr effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism involves carbon dioxide forming carbonic acid, which decreases pH. This pH change alters haemoglobin structure, reducing its oxygen affinity and promoting oxygen release where it is needed most.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Bohr effect describes how increased carbon dioxide causes decreased haemoglobin affinity for oxygen, facilitating oxygen unloading in tissues.","Increased carbon dioxide leads to decreased pH, which promotes the release of oxygen from haemoglobin.","The Bohr effect helps match oxygen delivery to metabolically active tissues that produce more carbon dioxide."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57975"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57975"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T22:00:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T22:01:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72505"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying 